text.tspan: Due to the nationwide lockdown and the temporary closure of schools in India, an online
survey was distributed via social media to overcome the social distance barrier. Although the
online method attributed to a large sample size, the researcher acknowledges that the survey may
be non-representative of the general population of high-schoolers in India, as not all segments of
the population have access to the internet. Therefore, this research is limited to private school
students representing the higher socio-economic status households of the country.
The researcher aimed to keep the survey questions precise and straightforward and kept
personal details to a minimum to ensure an honest and thoughtful reply. However, the researcher
had little control over who completed the survey and who had access to it. Furthermore, the
researcher acknowledges that the respondents may have failed to provide honest answers due to
inaccurate self-perceptions and biased recalls of past events (Murg, 2010). Some respondents
may have submitted multiple entries resulting in a biased result.
Procedure
The researcher conducted a quantitative and qualitative analysis by distributing an online
survey, made via Google Forms, to private high school students studying across various cities in
India, including Dehradun, Mumbai, Patiala, Darjeeling, Siliguri, Mhow, and Indore. The survey
was made available to students from May 31, 2020, to June 9, 2020. Although the last date for
the nationwide COVID-19 lockdown was May 31, 2020, schools all across India were shut down
throughout the dates for the survey, and the questions were primarily based on the students'
lockdown experience in general. Permission was granted from a school in Indore to send the
